 0065:     """
 0066:     An atom group. This class is based on the :class:`Atom` class, except that
 0067:     it uses :ref:`atom types <atom-types>` instead of elements, and all
 0068:     attributes are lists rather than individual values. The attributes are:
 0069: 
 0070:     =================== =================== ====================================
 0071:     Attribute           Type                Description
 0072:     =================== =================== ====================================
 0073:     `atomType`          ``list``            The allowed atom types (as :class:`AtomType` objects)
 0074:     `radicalElectrons`  ``list``            The allowed numbers of radical electrons (as short integers)
 0075:     `charge`            ``list``            The allowed formal charges (as short integers)
 0076:     `label`             ``str``             A string label that can be used to tag individual atoms
 0077:     `lonePairs`         ``list``            The number of lone electron pairs
 0078:     =================== =================== ====================================
 0079: 
 0080:     Each list represents a logical OR construct, i.e. an atom will match the
 0081:     group if it matches *any* item in the list. However, the
 0082:     `radicalElectrons`, and `charge` attributes are linked
 0083:     such that an atom must match values from the same index in each of these in
 0084:     order to match.
 0085:     """
 0086: 
+0087:     def __init__(self, atomType=None, radicalElectrons=None, charge=None, label='', lonePairs=None):

 1011:         # It only makes sense to compare a Group to a Group for subgraph

 1470:         """
 1471:         Step 1. Classify all atoms as Cb, Cbf1, Cbf2, Cbf3, ignoring all non-benzene carbons
 1472: 
 1473:         Every carbon atom in a benzene ring can be defined as one of the following:
 1474:         Cb - benzene carbon in exclusively one ring. Can have one single bond
 1475:         Cbf - general classification for any benzene carbon that connects two fused benzene rings
 1476:         Cbf1 - Cbf that is bonded to exactly one other Cbf, exclusively in two different benzene rings
 1477:         Cbf2 - Cbf that is bonded to exactly two other Cbfs, exclusively in two different benzene ring
 1478:         Cbf3 - Cbf that is bonded to exactly three other Cbfs, exclusively in three different benzene rings
 1479: 
 1480:         The dictionary connectedCbfs has a cbf atom as key and the other Cbf atoms it is connected to as values
 1481: 
 1482:         Currently we only allow 3 Cbf atoms, so Cbf3 is not possible.
 1483:         """

 1492:         """
 1493:         #Step 2. Partner up each Cbf1 and Cbf2 atom
 1494: 
 1495:         For any fused benzene rings, there will always be exactly two Cbf atoms that join the benzne
 1496:         rings. Therefore, we can say that every Cbf1 atom has one 'partner' Cbf atom in which it
 1497:         share lies in two benzene rings with. If you try to draw a couple example PAHs, you'll
 1498:         find that Cbf2 atoms also have one exclusive 'partner', while Cbf3 atoms are actually
 1499:         'partnered' with every atom it is bonded to.
 1500: 
 1501:         Because of the current restriction of no more than three Cbf atoms, partnering up every
 1502:         Cbf1 is sufficient. If we ever decide to relax this restriction, we will need more code
